default2.9 
defaultThe current narrow focus on employability
default can potentially exclude potential learners, including older prisoners, carers (including single mothers), high risk/lifer prisoners, prisoners from BAME backgrounds and prisoners with addictions or mental health problems and learners with learning difficu
defaultlties or disabilities.  
defaultThere
defaultfore there
default should be a broad vision of successful rehabilitation outcomes for learning.
default defaultLearning outcomes in prison should focus on giving prisoners the ability to cope with life in and out of prison (resilience), the ability t
defaulto desist from offending (desistance) and the ability to make a positive contribution to their family and community. These outcomes may encompass
default,
default but go far beyond
default,
default helping a prisoner have a job on release.
default 
default3.1 T
defaulthe MoJ are implementing significant cost savings as part of the ‘fair and sustainable’ agenda.  The PLA heard evidence 
defaultthat this policy was making it harder on the ground to achieve rehabilitation outcomes in custody.  Although the MoJ may be making initial savings in the prison estate, if this makes it harder to ac
defaulthieve rehabilitation and desista
defaultnce outcomes, then the pre
defaultdicted savings as a result of reduced reoffending will not be achieved.  Therefore a balance needs to be struck between the two competing policy agendas in order for the economics to add up.      
default&#xa0;
default3.2 O
defaultne Governor who spoke to the PLA said;
default 
default“The challenges are 
defaultcuts in funding, staffing cuts, low staff morale and being expected to do more with less. It is the most difficult time I have experienced in 25 years.  
defaultI would like a ‘utopia’ where a high level of education, training and work are avai
defaultlable to prisoners, but in reality all we can do is teach prisoners about doing an honest day
default’
defaults work and sticking to a job which involves doing the same tasks each day.  With another 5 million being taken out of the budget this year, partnerships are key. 
defaultWe have a contract to repair bed sheets and iron dressing downs. I realise this is low level work, but the contract has an output that can make us a profit”.
default3.3 
defaultA prison officer who attended the expert roundtable said
default “One of the biggest problems is cutti
defaultng staff numbers, so it will be difficult to get people to education.  If you’ve got someone on an education course but you can’t get them out they will loose interest.  It worries me as education is important.  With education behind them it’s more likely 
defaultthey won’t re-offend.  If they are serious about reducing reoffending them they can’t cut more staff”.
default  
default&#xa0;
default3.4 
defaultThe PLA were also told about specialist prison officer staff, for example those who provide sports courses in the gym, being moved back onto the w
defaultings for generic duties as staff are cut.  This reduces the amount of embedded learning and makes learning more siloed to just the education department, reducing the number of potential ‘hooks’ for learning
default that are so important to engage ‘hard to reach’ l
defaultearners
default.  
default&#xa0;
default3.5 
defaultAnother participant from the voluntary sector said they had noticed staff cuts making it harder for charities providing learning activities to gain access
default and be escorted;
default sometimes they would arrive but not be allowed in.
default So even when organisations offer to resource activity from charitable funds, prisons find it difficult to use them.
default One recommendation was to increase the ability of such organisations to carry keys.  One participant prison educator said they relied on in
defaultput from the voluntary sector to liven up her curriculum “
defaultprojects in prisons need to continue so that is the norm.  Prison education is really dry – we didn’t have their input it would be dire.  We need hooks.  They shouldn’t just come in once a year, it 
defaultshould be regular”.
default  
default&#xa0;
default3.6 
defaultA prison teacher told the PLA that due to staffing cuts, association time was being severely restricted, so prisoners were telling her they now had to decide between coming to education or taking a shower.  She had learners who v
defaultalued education and so came to class, but apologised for smelling as they had not washed for several days.  
