default4.1 In a nutshell, the impact of transforming rehabilitation on improving outcomes will depend crucially on how the changes are implemented and the relationships between the new and existing structures.  Uncoordinated or poorly thought through 
defaultimplementation would risk deterioration in outcomes.
default4.2 
defaultThe department with responsibility for ‘offender learning’ is Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS).  Through BIS the Offender Learning and Skills Service (OLASS) contracts are commissioned.  OLASS i
defaults currently in phase four, with three year contracts having been commissioned starting in summer 2012 to four educat
defaultion providers covering ten
default OLASS regions.  As these contracts will come to an end in summer 2015, a decision will need to be made by BIS whe
defaultther to extend the contracts or to re-tender.  This decision is however impacted by the Transforming Rehabilitation (TR) policies of the Ministry of Justice (MoJ).   TR and OLASS policies need to be joined-up if they are to lead to desistance outcomes.  Wi
defaultthout sufficient co-ordinat
defaultion there is a risk of conflict
default.
default4.
default3 
defaultTR has divided up England and Wales into 21 Contract Package Areas (CPAs)
default, which do not directly match the ten OLASS areas
default.  This add
defaults
default an additional layer of complexity to the regional systems
default and may therefore lead to reduced accountability.  This could ultimately lead to detrimental outcomes
default for the prisoner learners. 
defaultThis is exacerbated by the mismatch in time periods between the different contracts.
default4.
default4
default defaultUnder TR prisons will be divided into
default two types; resettlement and non-resettlement prisons.  Resettlement prisons are 
defaultintended
default 
defaultto be local to where the prisoner will be released.  The MoJ state that “
defaultIt is envisaged that the creation of resettlement prisons will present opportunities to creat
defaulte better continuity of service for offenders, in relation to wider mainstream and co-commissioned services. For instance, MoJ is testing, with the Department of Health, an ’end-to-end’ approach to tackling addiction from custody into the community”.
default  This 
default‘end to end’ approach should also be applied to education and training between the two departments for the benefit of the learner.  
default4.
default5 
defaultIt appears that prisoners will start their sentence in a resettlement prison, but if they are serving longer than six m
defaultonths in custody, they will be transferred to a non-resettlement prison, but will return to their resettlement prison three months prior to release.  This would mean a shift in curriculum focus for different prisons. OLASS contracts will need to be suffici
defaultently flexible to respond to the differing needs of the two types of prison populations.   
default4.
default6
default defaultResettlement prisons, being the first port of call for a prisoner, will also need to take a greater role in ensuring there is sufficient induction and assessmen
defaultt processes and to developing a learning plan, as this should then determine which non-resettlement prison a prisoner attends that would best meet their learning needs.    
default4.
default7 
defaultIn resettlement prisons education providers will be working with short sentence
defaultd prisoners with limited time for learning and competing priorities to sort out other resettlement issues such as accommodation, benefits, children and support for addictions if relevant.  However there will also need to be a focus on planning for transiti
defaulton to education, training or employment (ETE) after release.  
defaultIn order to make the most of the short time available, some learning opportunities should be available at evenings and weekends and in-cell.  
default4.
default8
default defaultI
defaultn non-resettlement prisons
default, with longer 
defaultsentenced prisoners,
default there may need to be additional flexibility to support distance learning and higher level qualifications to enable progression for those who have time to reach higher levels.  Non-resettlement prisons are also likely to be working or t
defaultraining prisons, therefore the contracts will need to enable providers to provide vocational and embedded learning to go alongside work activity.  
default4.
default9
default 
defaultNon-resettlement prisons may also have more very long sentenced prisoners and therefore will need to ensu
defaultre that informal and creative learning opportunities are available for those prisoners to be able to cope with their sentences.  
default4.
default10 
defaultIn non-resettlement prisons there will be longer-sentenced prisoners providing a more stable population with more time to
default focus on learning. 
defaultHowever t
defaulthere is a danger that due to the 
defaultcurrent 
defaultfocus placed on the beginning and end of the sentence, there is a gap in learning in the middle of the sentence
default.
default  
defaultTime spent in a non-resettlement prison is valuable time to learn knowle
defaultdge, skills and personal development.  If left until a prisoner arrives back at a resettlement prison in the last three months this will be too late and valuable time to be engaged in productive activity, working towards the process of desistance, will hav
defaulte been wasted.      
default4.
default11
default defaultLonger term prisoners coming back to resettlement prisons at the end of their sentence may have started a course of learning in the non-resettlement prison and therefore require support to complete that course of study and take th
defaulte appropriate assessment to gain the qualification. 
default4.
default12 
defaultCRCs, paid by their ability to reduce reoffending, will be interested to work with OLASS providers to ensure the learning in prison is preparing prisoners towards desistance.  However currently OLAS
defaultS providers have no incentive to consider whether the learning and curriculum they provide contributes to desistance.  They are encouraged to think about employability, although are paid by numbers of accreditations rather than by outcomes of prisoners ent
defaultering employment.  
default4.
default13 
defaultT
defaulthe Ministry of Justice has stated that there is a ‘complex relationship’ between employment and reducing reoffending and that there are other factors which contribute to the process of desistance.  This could therefore lead to c
defaultonflict between the CRC who will
default favour a desistance-led approach and the OLASS providers who
default will favour an accreditation / employability
default-led approach.
default  
default&#xa0;
default4.
default14 
defaultUnder current TR arrangements CRCs will not have a say in the education and training provision 
defaultin non-resettlement prisons.  However, what happens in non-resettlement prisons will impact the CRCs
default’
default ability to achieve their reducing reoffending results.  If the time in the non-resettlement prison has been used productively, including access to learnin
defaultg, the prisoner in question will be in a better position to prepare for resettlement than a prisoner who has not been engaged in learning.  By aligning the focus on rehabilitation outcomes of primary and secondary desistance for both the OLASS provider and
default CRC, this should enable them to work closer together for the benefit of the prisoner learner whether at a resettlement or non-resettlement prison.  Without this, there risks an approach which focuses solely on the final months of a sentence and valuable t
defaultime earlier in the sentence to engage and progress with learning has been lost.   
default&#xa0;
default4.1
default5
default 
defaultAnother issue is the 
defaultmismatch in 
defaultcontract length
defaults which adds additional complexity.  The c
defaultontract length for CRCs will be 7 to 10 years, with the option to extend by 
defaultup to 3 years.  Current
defaultly OLASS contracts are for 3
default years, with the option to extend.  The PLA roundtables heard from practitioners about the disruption caused each time the contracts are re-tendered and the length of time it can take to ‘bed-in’.  OLASS p
defaultroviders also told us that the short contract terms can disincentivise investment in capital projects, such as vocational training or social enterprises.  Another disadvantage of shorter contract terms is that it prevents the collection of longitudinal dat
defaulta about ‘what works’.  This does not matter when the focus is on output measures such as number of accreditations, how ever if there is a move towards outcome desistance based measures, then shorter contracts will make longitudinal data collection of outco
defaultmes more difficult.  These considerations must of course be balanced with the need to hold providers to account and therefore if contract terms were lengthened, other strong measures of accountability would need to be in place. 
default4.1
default6
default 
defaultAnother concern about 
defaultthe contract length for CRCs is that prisoners who will not be released within that contract term may ‘fall between the gaps’ as CRCs have no incentive to be interested in that prisoner as they will not impact their payment by results.  Therefore mechanism
defaults
default should be in place to ensure longer sentenced prisoners have access to learning, despite not being released within the contract term.  
default4.17
default defaultUnder TR prisoners subject to Multi Agency Public Protection Arrangements (MAPPA) and those who pose highest risk
default to the public will be managed by the new National Probation Service, rather than by the CRCs.  Therefore NPS will need to work more closely with the education provider to ensure that these ‘high risk’ and MAPPA prisoners are able to access appropriate lea
defaultrning.  
defaultGiven that these prisoners are most likely to find it challenging to find traditional employment, an OLASS approach solely focused on employment is likely to exclude these prisoners.  Therefore, as described in chapter one, a ‘whole-person’ and des
defaultistance – led approach to learning would be of benefit, for example by ensuring that Offending Behaviour Programmes are combined with appropriate personal and social development and other learning activities to ensure the soft skills / intermediate outcome
defaults are pract
defaultised and developed over time (NOMS, 2013).
default&#xa0;default4.18
default defaultTherefore in formulating sentence plans and learning plans there should be mechanisms to ensure a joined up approach between the NPS and OLASS providers to meet the needs of these prisoners. 
