default&#xa0;defaultAnnex AdefaultSummary of evidence (See full report for more detail and additional examples)default&#xa0;defaultAnnex BdefaultExecutive Summary of ‘Smart Rehabilitation: Learning how to get better outcomes’ defaultPLA recommendationsdefaultThe Prisoner Learning Alliance, after consultation with its 16 members and over 50 teachers, prisoners, ex-prisoners, Governors, officers and other stakeh
defaultolders, have developed a set of three key principles for the future of prisoner learning.  At this time of unprecedented change in the Criminal Justice System, it is important for government departments and other stakeholders to keep these key principles i
defaultn mind.  Prisoner learning should be; outcome-focused, joined-up and value-driven.  The PLA makes 17 recommendations for how to achieve this;  
defaultOutcome focused:defaultJoined – up:defaultImproved co-ordination defaultbetween government departments.default  Prisoner learning is impacted by policies from multiple departments; BIS, MoJ, DoE, DWP, DCLG, Home Office and the Treasury.  This is a time of unprecedented change; recent policies from each of these departments have the p
defaultotential to conflict.  Urgent consideration is needed of how these policies can be joined up in order to achieve positive rehabilitation outcomes. In order to achieve the best outcomes and value for money, policies should be co-ordinated and outcome target
defaults aligned.  Parliament should consider how best it can ensure that there is scrutiny of these different government departments and how effectively they work together to achieve overall rehabilitation outcomes.    
